text: People need to know that Deadpool ISN'T a Superhero. He's a mercenary with super-human regenerative powers and multiple personality disorders who mostly does everything for money. Yeah, there will be grandstanding with cheesy/lame 1-liners because the guy is crazy, says whatever comes to his fractured mind. No one in the comic can stand him because he NEVER shuts up and enjoys doing the killing -- most of the time. If you understand this, you will like the movie. If you go in thinking he's supposed to be like one of the Avengers or an X-men, you will be sorely disappointed.

text: That quote about Deadpool wearing red and the guy wearing brown pants reminds me of a joke from Bill Engvall.  There's this pirate captain sailing upon his ship out at sea with his crew; man in the crow's nest calls out an enemy ship on the horizon, and the captain says "Bring me, my red, shirt." He gets it on and they succeed without any losses. Next day a crew member asks why the red shirt, captain says, "It's so that, in case I get shot and bleed, the crew won't notice and they'll continue fighting". The guy in the crow's nest calls out 20 enemy ships on the horizon and the captain replies with, "Bring me my Brown Pants!" XD   Part of me feels like someone in production either heard that joke, or watched Bill Engvall or Blue Collar Comedy

text: I kinda wish the tone didn't waver so much. For a comic book, that tonal impermanence, always shifting and changing, can be effective story-telling. But in a movie, especially one trying to capture the attention of a couple of different age demographics, despite the liberal use of a hard R rating, that can muddle up the final product.  I wasn't expecting it to be straightforward-linear-movie-film-for-theaters out the gate. An actually origin story. I hope those flashback moments are given more levity and irreverence. You can't generate sympathy for such a crass, vulgar, 4th-wall breaking, meta character by showing how he USED to be. There are more clever ways to inform Wade Wilson's character through his actions.  Bah, now I'm rambling. I'm hyped for this flick. Just... cautiously hyped.

text: After the disappointment that was Green Lantern according to some people,i didn't see Ryan Reynolds playing another super hero or anti-hero ever again in his career.But than again,if Ben Affleck can put on the Bat suit after many criticized him for his portrayal of Dare Devil,one can only hope this movie will be good,if not great.  This role seems more fitted to Ryan Reynolds acting and/or comedic skills than such a serious character like Green Lantern.He was not the right guy for that role.So far this trailer shows promise with its material and mature approach.Hopefully it wont be marginalized the same way Watchmen was for its content.Some people have a distorted view of superheroes/comic books expecting it to be squeaky clean like Spider-Man,Superman or some brady bunch episode.

text: Quite frankly, the marketing campaign for the Deadpool movie has been *spot on*. Absolutely perfect. Starting off with the "accidental" release of that wonderful test footage. The announcement on April fools that had Deadpool saying that his movie will be rated R. Deadpool narrating a trailer for his own trailer. Deadpool crashing the Fantastic four trailer. And within this trailer as well... a jab at the green lantern movie... If this movie turns out to be *half* as masterfully crafted as the marketing campaign thus far, then the likes of The Dark Knight, Iron man, The Avengers and Guardians of the Galaxy will have something to bow down to.

text: To those arguing about whether or not the Green Lantern reference is "breaking the fourth wall," it is. Breaking the fourth wall means the character does something that indicates that this character isn't real, or that they know they are in a movie (or tv show, or play, etc.). By alluding to GL, this also alludes to Ryan Reynolds existing, which means this character is not a real person. And to those calling it an "Easter Egg" I say this: you have to hunt for Easter eggs, just like the real things. They are not shouted at you, nor are eggs hurled at you on Easter.

text: Is swearing and gore supposed to make this movie good? Because so far that's the only things that are different from other weak and poorly written superhero films, and that doesn't make the film any better, just a little embarassing. Superheroes are supposedly kids stuff, or at least whole family stuff. A superhero that kids can't even watch is supposed to be fun? Well he's targeted audience is like one, single generation, because neither would aged adults watch it cuz they would judge it as silly, nor kids because of gore and cursing. And even to me as an adult comic book fan, at least from the trailer alone, there's nothing in there that would make me want to see this. The actor also carries a bad name around, joking about how bad was green lantern movie doesn't make me forget that he did a HORRIBLE job both as green lantern, and as deadpool in Wolverine movie.

text: Kinda relitiveDeadpool: Red band Speculation I have a feeling the deadpool movie not going to be too good but everyone is going to back it up because its deadpool, don't get me wrong deadpool is my favorite superhero and I love the comics and the game esspecialy the humor, but the trailer for it kinda put me off.  The humor was... different to the comics, it was more "random" and seemed more forced, and unnessisary. And when he goes "I'm going to touch myself tonight" after fighting tons of what we know are bad guys and inhaling somke from his guns made me kinda upset. This goes for the wrighting, its just dosent feel right. The CGI and cinematoegraphy looks good, yet we don't know much about the actual story other than how its a origin story (I hope it dosent drone on). It dosent even show us why he fights crime. (I mean most of us already know why but its kinda crutial to put in a trailer.)  Well its just a trailer and I'm going to watch it anyway, maybe it will be great. But we just have to wait and see.  Don't agree with me, then explain your opinions and why you disagree. Thanks for reading.

text: Love Deadpool as he's my favorite comic book character of all time--the only one I ever liked enough to actually buy a comic (outside of like, Archie), mostly because of the humor. It's something I can really relate to--the sort of inside jokes for the culturally literate. Heck, I actually research the stuff he references sometimes.  Hopefully though, the jokes are better than (most) of these. Sorry, call me a conservative but I know Deadpool can be funny without the cursing or the R-rated humor and obscenities. Though I can appreciate the need for the R rating, I found Deadpool funniest breaking the 4th wall and making references in the comics or just being in absurd stories. Love the Green Lantern joke and it took awhile to get the brown pants joke. So, here's hoping for¬†more intelligent humor jokes¬†that transcends the crude.

text: The Charleston shooting is yet another massacre orchestrated by people with advanced technology. The victims under the control of this technology, such as Dylann Roof, are known as or "zips" or "zipper guns". If you have watched The Sopranos (the characters are based on people from my local area), you may have heard them use the term "zip". This word is used to describe assassins from Italy who are used to do the dirty work for Tony Soprano and his crew, and their presence in the show is a metaphor for people under the control of this technology. There are a few scenes in The Sopranos where Tony plays golf, which is a metaphor for radome sites such as the CIA-ran Menwith Hill in the UK. These facilities give use of their technology to The Freemasons. There is another mention in the media of this technology in an interview between Bill O'Reilly and Jon Stewart. Jon Stewart says, "Oh come on Bill, we're both members of the media elite here", to which Bill O'Reilly replies, "Oh yeah? How many zipper guns you got?".  The nature of the technology itself is described when British TV presenter Johnny Vaughan interviewed Al Pacino. Johnny Vaughan asked Al Pacino a how he got into character for the roles he played, to which Pacino replied, "You know, it's like you put on a suit, and get inside a box." Vaughan answered, "So it's a suit in a box?". This technology can hijack the victim's body, seemingly like some virtual reality experience for the user, where they put on a "suit" (and I assume some form of headgear), which enables them to experience life through the eyes of the technologically-controlled victim. Then they can do whatever they like, which often involves going on rampages and killing large numbers of innocent people.  There are lots of clues as to the identity of the culprits within the details of the massacre itself; the Charleston shooting was conducted by someone with a bowl cut haircut, which is because of some guy from around my area who looks like Peter Beardsley. I think his name might be Tom or Adam, with the Cowan, Howell, Hamilton, Howe, Metcalfe and Hodgson families being frequent users of this technology. The Sandy Hook massacre was conducted by these same people, they selected the school Sandy Hook because of the name Sandy, and the fact that the person who committed the massacre was called Adam is no coincidence. There was a shooting at Arapahoe High School because someone in the UK was referred to as a "ho" and then there was a trend on Twitter, "#PunkRockHo", which escalated to the Apapahoe shooting (A Rapper Ho).

text: The only issues I have from seeing this trailer is:  1. A lot of the action scenes in the trailer seems to be on that highway overpass. I'm hoping that his origin story doesn't take an hour so we get action the last 30 minutes or so. And also more variety to where he goes.¬†If we do get a long origin story, I trust that Deadpool's character will make it a fun ride though.  2. I felt like the test footage nailed the "red suit, brown pants" joke. Maybe having a pedestrian passing by, staring at Deadpool until he starts, "You must be wondering why the red suit, blah blah blah" Then when he notices the trucks, he turns to the camera (or back to the pedestrian) and finishes the "brown pants" portion. text: Lots of people asking about 4th wall breaking and how heavily it will feature. I'm sure most of us here have read the comics and know that deadpool breaking the forth wall happens most often when it's just deadpool and the audience alone. He talks to us when no one is around. There will be lines here and there that will be directed towards the camera, and there will be references to real world things like the green animated suit. This is a forth wall break because its not acknowledged by the people in the movie. The forth wall is practically a deadpool trademark. He'll be breaking that more than he's breaking bones. Trust me.

text: BEFORE YOU COMMENT HERE: If you don't know about him, please research before commenting. This movie has every right to be rated r because that IS his character. Deadpool is a comedic anti-hero psychopath. TO THE PARENTS: Do NOT hope this rating will be lowered to pg-13 so your kids can see it. Regardless of what you may think, not every comic book superhero is "clean" and kid friendly. If they want to see it that bad then YOU will have to go with them. This movie will be VERY inappropriate. TO THE KIDS: You probably shouldn't even watch this till you're older. Half of these jokes you probably won't even understand. If you really want to see this movie have your parent take you. That's the ONLY way you'll see it in theaters. TO THE DISNEY MARVEL FANS: This will be COMPLETELY different than what you're used to in the previous marvel movies. just have an open mind and most likely you will enjoy this movie. THAT IS ALL. Im baffled that through all Ryan Renolds talk of being such a super fan to Deadpool, he acts nothing like him, at least from the whiffed humor here in this trailer. text: !!Message to Fox. Take mind of what James Gunn's response to the success of Deadpool because it is true. Green lighting uninspired rate R movies isn't going to get the same success. It's the originality, writing and true to the source material that captured the attention of fans. People wanted it R rate because that is what the comic was like. Instead of presuming to know what people want try reading comments and asking people. Also understand that the comic book community is your target audience. A lot of people who don't like superheros don't usually go see a superhero movie no matter how generic you make it. Stop learning the wrong messages from successful films. People liked it because it was closer to what they were familiar with not simply because it was rated R.
